# Scraper Rules

These sources are unofficial/undocumented and *will* break without notice. Treat
every scraper as hostile input.

## Required for every scraper module

- Prefer direct `fetch` against internal JSON endpoints over headless browser
  rendering (Playwright) — only fall back to Playwright if the store requires JS
  execution to expose data.
- Wrap the entire fetch+parse in try/catch. On failure: log the error with source
  name and timestamp, return an empty array, never throw up to the job runner.
- Validate the response shape (zod schema per source) before mapping to
  `NormalizedDeal`. If validation fails, treat it as a scraper break, not a data
  error — log loudly, don't silently drop malformed data into the DB.
- Rate-limit yourself: minimum delay between requests, sensible page-size batching.
  Don't hammer the endpoint just because there's no published limit.
- No hardcoded auth tokens or cookies committed to the repo, even ones scraped from
  a public page — pull from env if a session is ever needed.

## When a scraper breaks

- Don't silently "fix" it by loosening validation — confirm the actual response
  shape changed, update the zod schema and mapper together, and note the change
  in a comment with the date.
- You don't need to manually record the breakage anywhere — the cron route
  calls `recordSourceRun()` on every run (`040-database.mdc`,
  `070-implementation-plan.mdc`), so a failing scraper shows up on `/status`
  automatically. Your job when fixing one is just to fix the code; the
  dashboard reflects it on the next successful run.
- If asked to write a new scraper from scratch: propose the endpoint(s) and
  response shape first, based on what's actually observed in the network tab —
  don't invent an endpoint URL from pattern-matching to similar sites.
